<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,837,1512]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,837,862]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Head large oval, pale yellowish brown including posterior margin and gular sclerite; maxillary palp (
<figureCitation box="[159,248,876,900]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
) with RO located in the basal third; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[769,855,876,900]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
) 4-segmented, flagellum as in 
<figureCitation box="[1207,1295,876,900]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1308,1322,876,900]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1935,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,839,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-228@8.[188,1398,839,1914]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Meropelopia americana (Fittkau), larva (A–F). A—maxillary palpus, arrow indicating sensillum b; B—antennal flagellum; C—mandible, arrow pointing to accessory tooth; D—pseudoradula; E—ligula; F—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">3</figureCitation>
<superScript attach="left" box="[1322,1335,873,887]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">rd</superScript>
segment sitting on membranous pedestal; mandible (
<figureCitation box="[653,742,912,936]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6D</figureCitation>
) with small basal tooth pointed apically; dorsomental plates (
<figureCitation box="[159,245,948,972]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
) present with 6 large teeth plus 1 small outer lateral and small one fused to short medial projection; pseudoradula with granular surface coarser and expanded near the middle; ligula (
<figureCitation box="[1012,1095,984,1008]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
) with long outer laterals about twice the length of median tooth, inner laterals turned slightly outwards; ventral cephalic setae and VP as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6G, S</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[212,226,1056,1080]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1964,1987]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,955,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-307@15.[188,1398,955,1943]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Prodiamesa olivacea (Meigen), larva (A–E). A—Head, showing dark ventral pattern; B—labrum with premandible; C—antenna, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible; E—mentum, III-instar." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">9</figureCitation>
and S 
<figureCitation box="[299,328,1056,1080]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1628,1651]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,844,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-316@16.[188,1398,844,1607]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 10. Brillia parva Johannsen, larva (A–F). A—Head, ventral, arrow pointing to SSm; B—clypeus (Clyp) and labral sclerites (Sc1, Sc2); C—antenna, arrow pointing to pale ring; D—mandible; E—mentum; F—posterior end of abdomen." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">10</figureCitation>
long simple setae, SSm seta with multi-branched, slightly anterior to S9, VP posterolateral of S9 and S10; body with weak lateral fringe extending to abdominal segment 6; posterior end of abdomen as in 
<figureCitation box="[1343,1431,1092,1116]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6H</figureCitation>
, procercus with 12–13 apical setae; small claws on posterior parapods with drawn-out thin bases (
<figureCitation box="[1238,1317,1128,1152]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-163@12.[188,1398,481,1768]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Macropelopia decedens (Walker). larva (A–I). A—maxillary palpus, arrow pointing to RO; B—antenna; C—antennal flagellum, arrow pointing to segment 3; D—mandible, arrow pointing to basal tooth; E—dorsomental plates; F—ligula, paraligula and hypopharyngeal pecten; G—ventral cephalic setae (S9, S10, SSm) and ventral pore (VP); H—posterior end of abdomen; I—claws of posterior parapod, arrow pointing to elongated bases." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,837,1512]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1164,1188]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="1">Notes.</emphasis>
So far this is the only known Nearctic species, and our specimen agrees with 
<bibRefCitation author="Roback, S. S." box="[1175,1363,1164,1188]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref27486" refString="Roback, S. S. (1978) The immature chironomids of the eastern United States III. Tanypodinae-Anatopynini, Macropelopini and Natarsiini. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 129, 151 - 202." type="journal article" year="1978">Roback’s (1978)</bibRefCitation>
larval description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,837,1512]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,445,1236,1261]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="1">Ecology and habitat.</emphasis>
Larvae were mainly found in moss. Larvae feed on smaller invertebrates, including Protozoa, Ostracoda, Crustacea and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Roback 1978)" baseAuthorityName="Roback" baseAuthorityYear="1978" box="[519,888,1272,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Ceratopogonidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Roback, S. S." box="[725,880,1272,1296]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref27486" refString="Roback, S. S. (1978) The immature chironomids of the eastern United States III. Tanypodinae-Anatopynini, Macropelopini and Natarsiini. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 129, 151 - 202." type="journal article" year="1978">Roback 1978</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The species is reported to occur in streams with temperature 14–18°C (
<emphasis box="[408,422,1312,1330]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">X</emphasis>
= 13°C), pH 6.01–7.0 (
<emphasis box="[688,702,1312,1330]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">X</emphasis>
= 6.8) and altitude 
<quantity box="[921,1040,1308,1332]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.57" metricValueMax="6.09" metricValueMin="3.05" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="m" value="457.0" valueMax="609.0" valueMin="305.0">305–609m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Roback, S. S." box="[1055,1210,1308,1332]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref27486" refString="Roback, S. S. (1978) The immature chironomids of the eastern United States III. Tanypodinae-Anatopynini, Macropelopini and Natarsiini. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 129, 151 - 202." type="journal article" year="1978">Roback 1978</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,837,1512]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,1343,1368]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="1">Sampling sites.</emphasis>
We found the larvae inhabiting streams in all the provincial parks and districts located in our study area.
</paragraph>
